  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential Imprisonment\n- Up to 10-20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Sentences can be consecutive if multiple charges are involved\n\n2. Financial Penalties\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potentially hundreds of thousands of dollars per violation\n- Forfeitures of assets obtained through illegal activities\n\n3. Additional Consequences\n- Criminal record\n- Asset seizure\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Restrictions on future financial activities\n\n4. Specific Statute Details\n- Violations typically prosecuted under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957\n- Penalties vary based on specific circumstances of the offense\n- Aggravating factors can increase potential sentences\n\nThe exact penalties depend on factors like:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Specific nature of the laundering\n- Prior criminal history\n- Whether the offense involved other criminal activities\n\nNote: Legal interpretations can be complex, and actual penalties are determined by federal prosecutors and courts based on specific case details.",
